"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150890","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-11-05","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Dissolution.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150890/answer",,,,,,"2019-11-05T13:23:23.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150890/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150890/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-21","Food: UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the Answer of 19 December 2017 to Question 118358 on Agricultural Products: UK Trade With EU, what progress her Department has made on developing the UK’s system for the management of agri-food imports and exports with EU countries.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","2758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150891","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-10-28","<p>The level of remuneration under Smart Export Guarantee tariffs will be determined by suppliers, in line with the aim of moving away from direct subsidy to cost reflective pricing and competitive market-based solutions.</p><p>The Government have asked Ofgem to report annually on the provisions made by suppliers for smaller scale exporters, including the range, nature and uptake of Smart Export Guarantee tariffs.</p><p>The Government will actively monitor the development of this market and will consider reviewing these tariff setting arrangements, if it becomes clear that small generators are not able to access a competitive range of export tariff options.</p>","Spelthorne","Kwasi  Kwarteng","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150891/answer",,,,,,"2019-10-28T13:23:58.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150891/answer","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150891/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-10-21","Renewable Energy: Smart Export Guarantee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps her Department is taking to ensure (a) competitive and (b) fair market tariffs are available under the Smart Export Guarantee.","false","Biography information for Gillian Keegan","Chichester","Gillian Keegan","2902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150892","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-28","<p>​The British Government remains deeply concerned about the deteriorating situation in the North-West and South-West (Anglophone) regions of Cameroon. We continue to raise these concerns at the highest levels, including with the Government of Cameroon, at the UN and with international partners. During briefings on conflict prevention, peace and security at the UN Security Council in October, the UK welcomed the National Dialogue that took place in Cameroon from 30 September – 4 October as an initial step to bring parties together to work towards peace. The subsequent release of 333 prisoners arrested in connection with the crisis was also a welcome step. We hope these developments will build confidence among all parties to engage in efforts to bring peace to the North-West and South-West regions. Inclusive discussions about the root causes of people’s grievances and follow up on recommendations made at the National Dialogue are urgently needed to maintain momentum.</p>","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150892/answer",,,,,,"2019-10-28T15:18:42.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150892/answer","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150892/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-21","Cameroon: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to ensure a peaceful resolution to the conflict in Cameroon.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","2903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150893","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-28","<p>In September 2019 we announced funding of £200 million for new equipment to drive earlier diagnosis of cancer and improve survival. More than 300 diagnostic machines will be funded across the country, replacing outdated MRI machines, CT scans and breast screening equipment with cutting edge technology.</p><p>The NHS Long Term Plan sets a clear ambition that where appropriate ever person diagnosed with cancer should have access to personalised care by 2021. Personalised care is made up of four interventions that used to be referred to as the Support Package:</p><p>- Personalised care and support planning based on holistic needs assessments;</p><p>- End of treatment summaries;</p><p>- Health and wellbeing information and support; and</p><p>- A Cancer Care Review with their general practitioner.</p><p>The NHS Cancer Programme aims to improve access to cancer Clinical Nurse Specialists (CNS) for all cancer patients when they need it, including those with secondary breast cancer. The NHS Long Term Plan commitment is that all patients, including those with secondary cancers, will have access to the right expertise and support, including a CNS or other support worker by 2021.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150893/answer",,,,,,"2019-10-28T15:45:53.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150893/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150893/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-21","Breast Cancer: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to improve the (a) diagnosis, (b) treatment and (c) support provided to people with secondary breast cancer.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","2689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150894","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-29","<p>The interim NHS People Plan was published on 3 June 2019 and sets out the type of workforce, and future staff and leadership culture the National Health Service will need to develop, to ensure the successful delivery of the NHS Long Term Plan.</p><p> </p><p>The final NHS People Plan will be informed by the Cancer Workforce Plan for England, published in December 2017 by Health Education England. This set out plans to expand capacity and skills in the cancer workforce, including targeting additional training support for seven priority professions such as clinical radiology, histopathology, oncology and diagnostic and therapeutic radiography. Since 2017 there has been a net increase of 833 full time equivalent staff across the seven priority professions.</p><p> </p><p>The full NHS People Plan will be published in the next few months and will set out a clear framework for collective action on workforce priorities over the next five years.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150894/answer",,,,,,"2019-10-29T12:38:11.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150894/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150894/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-21","Cancer: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether the forthcoming NHS people plan will include a fully costed plan for increasing the cancer workforce.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","2759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150895","Home Office","false","2019-10-24","<p>Once the United Kingdom leaves the EU, we expect that UK residents travelling to EU countries with their firearm or shotgun will no longer be able to use a European Firearms Pass. They would instead have to comply with whatever licensing or other requirements that other EU countries impose.</p><p>This will not impact on the UK’s domestic firearms controls. EU nationals bringing firearms temporarily into the UK will continue to require a visitors’ firearm permit issued by a UK police force.</p><p>The Government has published a technical notice setting out information on the potential loss of the European Firearms Pass, to allow UK businesses and citizens to make informed plans and preparations, on gov.uk.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150895/answer",,,,,,"2019-10-24T15:33:15.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150895/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1150895/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-21","Firearms: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether European Firearms Passes currently held will be valid in the weeks immediately after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Sir Charles Walker","2760"
